@*
    Example 1 — Basic usage.

    The minimum viable share control: a label and a list of destinations
    you supply. With Strategy.Auto (the default), a device that has a
    native share sheet opens that instead of the list — so on a phone
    this renders one button and shows the OS sheet, and on a desktop the
    same button opens the list below it.

    CopyLabel is what makes the copy item appear. There is no default,
    because a default would be a hardcoded English string. Once you
    supply it, supply CopiedLabel and CopyFailedLabel too: copying is
    silent, so without them the user gets no confirmation either way.

    Note CopyFailedLabel says what to do instead, not just that it
    failed. Copy can fail for reasons invisible to the user — insecure
    context, denied permission, no async clipboard — so the message has
    to be actionable. See docs/accessibility.md.

    An interactive render mode is required. Under static SSR the markup
    renders but OnAfterRenderAsync never fires, so the button cannot open
    the sheet, write the clipboard, or move focus.
*@

@page "/examples/share-chooser/basic"
@rendermode InteractiveServer
@using LilyDesignSystem.Blazor.Helpers

<ShareChooser Label="Share this page"
             Title="An article worth reading"
             Targets="@Targets"
             CopyLabel="Copy link"
             CopiedLabel="Link copied"
             CopyFailedLabel="Could not copy — copy it from the address bar" />

@code {
    // No social endpoints ship with the package: which networks belong in
    // a product is an editorial and privacy decision, and share URLs
    // change. Href is a function, so you own the whole URL and its
    // encoding.
    private static readonly ShareTarget[] Targets =
    {
        new()
        {
            Id = "mastodon",
            Label = "Mastodon",
            Href = (url, title, _) =>
                $"https://mastodon.social/share?text={Uri.EscapeDataString(title)}%20{Uri.EscapeDataString(url)}",
        },
        new()
        {
            Id = "email",
            Label = "Email",
            // mailto: hands off to a mail client, so a new tab would just
            // leave an empty one behind.
            NewTab = false,
            Href = (url, title, _) =>
                $"mailto:?subject={Uri.EscapeDataString(title)}&body={Uri.EscapeDataString(url)}",
        },
    };
}
